 1392":"1330–vóór 1392","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1315–1392":"1315–1392","1348–1391":"1348–1391","1348–Male":"1348–Overleden","1352–Male":"1352–Overleden","1359–1395":"1359–1395","1360–1395":"1360–1395","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","about 1360":"circa 1360","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1391":"1391","1348":"1348","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Bef 1392":"vóór 1392","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","Colthorpe, Oxfordshire, England":"Colthorpe, Oxfordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Kineton, Warwickshire, England":"Kineton, Warwickshire, England","Wheathill, Radstock, England":"Wheathill, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ipswell, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1330–Bef 1392":"1330–before 1392","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1315–1392":"1315–1392","1348–1391":"1348–1391","1348–Male":"1348–Deceased","1352–Male":"1352–Deceased","1359–1395":"1359–1395","1360–1395":"1360–1395","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1391":"1391","1348":"1348","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","Bef 1392":"before 1392","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","Colthorpe, Oxfordshire, England":"Colthorpe, Oxfordshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Kineton, Warwickshire, England":"Kineton, Warwickshire, England","Wheathill, Radstock, England":"Wheathill, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Ipswell, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mile","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Aberdeenshire and Angus): occupational name from Middle English <i>milne</i> ‘mill’, also found as <i>mulne</i> in south and western England and <i>melne</i> in southeastern England. The Scottish name has been established in Ireland since the early 18th century, and has absorbed some cases of Irish   Moyle  . Compare   Mill   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Moyle","meanings":["Cornish: probably a nickname from Middle Cornish <i>mōl</i> ‘bald’, though its development to <i>Moyl(e)</i> is irregular.","Welsh: nickname from <i>moel</i> ‘bare, bald’, equivalent to Middle Cornish <i>mōl</i> (see 1 above).","English: variant of   Mule   or   Moule  ."]},{"name":"Milnes","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Milne  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare   Mills  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Mile was born in 1330, in Kineton, Warwickshire, England as the daughter of Henry Mile. She had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with John Br